Hi,

I don't know if the subject title originated with Miss Piggy of The
Muppetshow fame, but it surely describes the thoughts running around
my brain after reading the latest blog entry by Scott Krol over at
Shrapnel.

Short version : board wargames started off pretty simple, when it
caught on people wanted to differentiate themselves from the guys
playing risk hence the move to more complex games which translated to
monster games and other monstrosities like ASL which ultimately turned
out to be a dead-end evolution for boardgames and a factor in their
demise. Scott Krol observes the same evolution to complexity now
happening in mainstream games.

But what about wargames ? Is there also a drive to complexity, based
on elitism ?

I mean real wargames, not the click-'n-twitch RTS stuff ... uh-oh.

Implying that guys who play RTS games are brain-dead zombies who just
manage to &quot;win&quot; by being faster at clicking stuff on the screen may be
just a tad elitist, isn't it ? I mean, isn't a prerequisite for being
able to be good at clicking fast on various stuff located all over a
vast battlefield  a brain which keeps track of all the things in the
first place ? A brain which can think *and* react fast ?

A second element for consideration is that I heartily detest a
tendency in our current society which strives for egalitarianism by
bringing everyone down to the lowest common denominator. I believe in
a level playing field and a bar that is set at a certain height. If
100% of those that try don't make it, that is not problem hence no
&quot;solution&quot; (which mostly consists of lowering the bar) is needed. 80
IQ points guys are not going to be rocket scientists, no matter how
much money you throw at it.

So, two questions.

1) Does playing wargames really require more grey matter than playing
RTS games or are wargamers just slow thinkers ?

2) Is elitism a factor in wargaming and can it lead us to an
evolutionary dead-end ?

Greetz,

Eddy Sterckx
