Maybe not in the way that you mean.

If a new American Civil War game comes out tomorrow, I will probably
have a pretty good chance of diving right into it.  The teenager next
door probably will not.  Is it because I'm smarter?

Because if a new game based on, say, the Pokeman universe were to come
out tomorrow, I'd probably have a hard time getting into it.  Much
harder than that teen next door.

I think a key here is that historical wargames have an added layer of
complexity to make them historical.  By contrast, the Orcs versus Elves
genre can streamline mechanics to achieve better gameplay.  On average,
the rock-paper-scissors mechanic is going to be &quot;dumber&quot; than the
armor-slope-penetration mechanic; but on a case-by-case basis this is
not necessarily true.  Likewise on a player-by-player basis.

Historical wargames have a barrier to entry.  This added complexity is
of no value to someone who isn't interested in the historical nature of
the games.  That a wargame is too complicated or not fun sounds like a
refusal to exercise the gray matter, but its also a statement about what
the player sees as pleasurable about the game play.

So I think playing wargames requires a pre-requisite interest in the
history of warfare.  With that interest, the added details of the
wargame are part of the pleasure.  Take that away, and its a bunch of
useless chrome that inhibits good game design.

So does an interest in the history of warfare imply more engaged gray
matter than an interest in collecting Pokeman cards?  I would tend to
think so.  But my point is that most wargamers are such, not because
wargames provide them with the pinnacle in intellectual stimulation, but
because wargames are supporting a hobby in which they are already taking
part.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; 2) Is elitism a factor in wargaming and can it lead us to an
&gt; evolutionary dead-end ?
">

Not so much, if you buy my previous paragraphs.

Is someone really going to say, &quot;I'd like to read up some more on that
second battle at Manassas, but those wargame buffs are such a bunch of
self-important bastards that I guess I won't.&quot;
