I agree completely. I realized this when discussing a game I enjoyed with my
brother once. I wanted to get him interested in the game, but he remained
non-committal and evasive, even after he had tried the game out. Finally
after pushing him on the issue, he replied &quot;I like to get lost in my games,
I don't like it to feel like work&quot;.

Now my brother is not a stupid man by any means, but he does not have the
abiding interest in military history that I do, and he gets no enjoyment out
of playing a wargame. He much prefers a session of WoW, or a graphically
pleasing RTS than a thought provoking wargame any day of the week. The
gaming *hook* for him is his ability to forget real life for a while and
simply have some mindless fun. I don't think many (if any) wargames can fall
into the category of mindless fun. They all require some level of thought be
put into them to do well, and if you're not interested in what you are
required to think about, it feels like work.

RTS, FPS and other genre's require less thought be put into them and rely
more on an ability to react quickly to a situation (reflexes). So I don't
think we wargamers are elitists, rather we are simply a different set of
gamers. I personally hate any kind of reflex oriented game and play few if
any of those genres that rely heavily on reflexes. That doesn't mean I don't
have good reflexes (I do), it simply means I don't get any enjoyment out of
games that rely heavily on reflexes.

