I don't think &quot;elitism&quot; is the word I would use to describe a desire
for games to adhere to an historically accurate consensus of How
Things Actually Happened at the Battle of Whatever, any more than I
think the word describes an ability to appreciate of the art of cello
playing in philharmonic orchestras.  Ok, I'll own up to being a
&quot;grognard,&quot; but to me, that word does not imply any sort of elitism;
it implies a certain amount of knowledge of the subject at hand.  IMO,
being able to discuss the differences between a Douglas Dauntless and
a Curtis Helldiver doesn't make anyone an elitist, nor should anyone
who can't tell one from the other assume that it does.  However, those
who create wargames had better be aware of these things if they intend
to sell me a game, just as those who compose for cellos had better be
aware of *their* intended audience's expectations.

And I'm not sure what you mean by &quot;evolutionary dead end.&quot;  If you
mean that historical wargames (in contrast to generic shoot-em-ups)
will never appeal to the mass market, you're probably correct - but
then they never did - and I don't think that's a Bad Thing   If a PC
wargame sold 5,000 copies in 1985, it would have been considered
*wildly* successful.  A PC wargame that sold an identical amount in
2007 would be considered a failure when measured by the standards of
today's marketplace for PC games.  The potential market for PC games
has swelled beyond anyone (in 1985's) expectations, but the number of
players demanding historically accurate wargames has not, or at least,
not appreciably so.  I'm sure the developers are aware of all this and
devote the appropriate amount of funding (read: not much) to the
development of the kind of games that we here like best.  That can't
be helped, and as far as *this* wargamer is concerned, I see nothing
wrong with making do with less than state-of-the-art programs as long
as they fulfill my need to Be There, at an historic moment in the
history of warfare.  I don't happen to think my hobby is a cultural
dead end (and most certainly *not* an evolutionary dead end!), but
even if it's perceived that way by outsiders, so what?

The kind of wargames that the majority of the posters in this forum
enjoy will *never* be as popular as the kind of crap that tops the
best seller list.  So why are we still worrying about it?  ;-)

