The boardgame world at one point got stuck when almost all the games
produced were either unimaginative clones or monster games.
Playability and fun went right out of the window. A situation like
that is self-correcting as customers stopped buying the stuff and
companies went out of business but it took a decade for things to look
up again.

Oh, sure, the boardgames getting produced today are generally
excellent - way better than what it used to be even in the so-called
Golden Days - but while excellent boardgames can and are produced in a
P500 system, excellent computer wargames can't exist beneath a certain
sales threshold as it takes much more work to create a computer game
than it does a boardgame. And never mind the fact boardgame publishers
can ask more money for them too.

What I also want to avoid is the trap flight simmers find themselves
in : they've got a few excellent products, but rarely do they get new
toys to play with. I know why I stopped playing flight sims : because
the &quot;elitists&quot; demanded so many realistic features that it took the
fun right out of it for me, the average guy with an average flightsim
interest.

Looking down on &quot;easy&quot; wargames like Commander : Europe at War and
making fun of those who like the game is the first step on the road
taken by the hardcore, elitist flight simmers. See where it got them.

