I was there when it happened.

We had this DOS program which really could do anything the user ever
wanted - and the UI was in fact pretty ok. Then Windows 3.0 came along
and our customers simply demanded we provide them with a Windows
version of it which used those nice buttons and edit boxes. They
didn't care that the Windows version actually ran slower than the DOS
one and that the database driver was a bit iffy resulting in regular
lock-ups. At first I couldn't get my head around the fact that anyone
sane of mind and body would prefer what was unquestionably a worse
version of our product, but they did. Mostly because Windows offered a
friendly UI environment in which every program had a nice &quot;Ok&quot; button
to confirm something instead of having to hit &lt;F5&gt; in one and &lt;F7&gt; in
another.

UI matters - a lot.

